animals.name: Chico
animals.description: Chico runs the show! She has a great personality and is ok with all dog sizes, however, she doesn't get along with puppies.

animals.name: Hercules
animals.description: Hercules has some spunk and with the right friend, he'll have loads of fun chasing them around. Great with other small breeds but a little hesitant with larger dogs.

animals.name: Murphy
animals.description: Murphy LOVES to chill, but with the right friend he's down to run around and play chase. He's good with sharing toys and loves to fetch a ball...here or there.

animals.name: Stella
animals.description: Stella loves to fetch a ball... for hours on end. She's little but loves other friends and is always down for a good romp.

animals.name: Ralph
animals.description: Ralph loves adventure! He's great on hikes but could also be a couch potato. He's good with smaller dogs but is a little shy around larger breeds.

animals.name: Max
animals.description: Don't let Max's age fool you.. he's still got a lot of spunk in him. He's really good at being chill but does need to get out and stretch the legs, if you know what I mean. He loves to be chased and is known to make friends everywhere he goes. He is a little shy around bigger dogs at first but gets over that quickly.

animals.name: Milo
animals.description: Milo loves to run any agility course we can find. Typically, she's herding other dogs around so she's definitely in charge... but super sweet.

animals.name: Mabel
animals.description: Mabel is an absolute sweet heart. She'll play with just about any dog and is super gentle around smaller breeds. Give her a stick to fetch and she'll be content.

animals.name: Gus
animals.description: Gus is the perfect chill little dude. Super friendly but doesn't like men much so it might take awhile for him to warm up to you. Otherwise he's looking to make some furry connections!

animals.name: Brutus
animals.description: Brutus loves to love. Don't let the breed fool you, he's super sweet and as gentle as can be. He's really good with small dogs and enjoys low to medium energy. He is suspicious of nervous dogs so we do try to stay away from them.

animals.name: Scout
animals.description: Scout is a really chill dog but can easily pick up on any vibe. He's great with smaller dogs but a little hesitant with larger dogs. If he feels intimidated he may nip the air but he's never actually done harm to another dog. He's definitely a momma's boy. Oh, and he's great around female dogs.

animals.name: Argos
animals.description: Loves to be chased by his brother or any other pup, and loves to fetch a ball. Loads of love and energy in this little guy. Would do well with high energy puppers!

parks.name: Centennial Dog Park
parks.address: 2500 West End Ave, Nashville, TN, US, 37203
parks.description: Your pet will go wild for the chance to play off-leash at this fenced dog park, which includes a separate small dog area. Dogs must be vaccinated and licensed. Dogs are also allowed on the walking trails and open fields outside the park too. Public parking can be found at the Centennial Sportsplex on 25th Ave N.

parks.name: Shelby Dog Park
parks.address: 401 S 20th St, Behind the Shelby Park Community Center, Nashville, TN, US, 37206
parks.description: Dogs are allowed to play off-leash in a designated area of this park, located behind the Shelby Park Community Center.

parks.name: Edwin Warner Dog Park
parks.address: 50 Vaughn Rd, Across from the sports complex, Nashville, TN, US, 37221
parks.description: Bring your pet to run and play off-leash at this fenced dog park, which includes benches for owners to relax on and a doggie water fountain.

parks.name: Two Rivers Dog Park
parks.description: Two Rivers offers a wide open space for dogs to play, a wooded shady area, and a walking track.

parks.name: Riverfront Park Dog Park
parks.description: This new park located along the Cumberland River in Downtown Nashville gives beautiful views of the downtown skyline, sits on 11 acres of green space and includes Nashville's first and only downtown dog park. The downtown park includes the Ascend Amphitheater, solar charging stations, an 18,000 sq foot area of botanical gardens maintained by Cheekwood Botanical Gardens, plenty of seating for picnics, or enjoying the view of the Cumberland River from one of the giant porch swings. There are even areas within the park that offer free wifi. The dog park is 13,000 square feet of fenced, eco-friendly artificial turf, and is a great place for Fido to run and play. All the water fountains and bottle filling stations in the park include a fountain for Fido as well.

parks.name: Nashville Fairgrounds Dog Park
parks.description: Nashville Fairgrounds is now home to a dog park. This popular entertainment complex has a flea market, a speedway and hosts lots of events, but we're mainly interested in the brand spanking new dog park that they've just added. This is just part of the $275-million project that includes a Major League Soccer stadium. The car-themed, fenced-in park has agility tires, benches to relax on and AstroTurf that allows dogs to play whatever the weather. The park is open weekdays from 8:00am to 4:30pm.

parks.name: BarkPark
parks.description: BarkPark is pet-friendly. This private dog park is a great place to join classes, meet other pups and get some exercise. The park is equipped with splash pads, paddling pools and lots of fenced-in space for fun without a leash. Humans can watch their pups play from the cool covered benches. The Day Pass is $15 and applies to one dog and two humans. Monthly passes are $39 and annual passes are $199. The park is open every day of the week from 6am to 9pm.

parks.name: Nashboro Village Dog Park
parks.description: Nashboro Village Dog Park is pet-friendly. Bring your pooch to play with other pups at this park. The park is equipped with agility gear and a green space for a game of fetch. Dog owners are reminded to keep an eye on their pups as they play in the fenced area.

parks.name: Gulch Dog Park
parks.description: Gulch Dog Park is pet-friendly. Divided into two fenced sections; a large dog area approximately 3,500 square feet and a small dog area approximately 1,500 square feet, this park isn't your run-of-the-mill canine recreation area. The space will also serve as a community hub with a food truck and gathering area approximately 2,000 square feet. The park is open every day of the week from 7am to 10pm.

parks.name: William A Pitts Dog Park
parks.description: This park offers two acres of fenced-in space for dogs to play. Walking trails and a water fountain are nearby.

parks.name: Fenway's Dog Park at Moss-Wright Park
parks.description: Locals love this quiet, well-kept off-leash dog park, which is fully fenced with agility equipment, drinking water, trees, and benches.

parks.name: Stones River Greenway & Dog Park
parks.description: The Stones River Greenway is a pawsome dog-friendly trail that should be on the radar of every dog-and-human duo living in or visiting Nashville. Not only is the trail well-maintained and scenic, with plenty of easy parking options and amenities, it connects two of the best dog parks in Nashville! Wherever you start your adventure on the Stones River Greenway, you'll be able to get to a dog park in five miles or less. The journey there will take you over many scenic bridges and boardwalks where you'll be shaded by trees and surrounded by the sounds of the river.

parks.name: Whitsett Park
parks.description: Cozy, dog-friendly city park featuring walking trails, a sizable playground & creek access.

parks.name: Percy Warner Park
parks.description: Public forest & green space with hiking & equestrian trails, bicycle routes & athletic fields. Dog-friendly trails that should be on the radar of every dog-and-human duo living in Nashville.
